# slice - Rust

## Primitive Type [slice](#)

1.0.0 ·

Expand description

A dynamically-sized view into a contiguous sequence, `[T]`. Contiguous here means that elements are laid out so that every element is the same distance from its neighbors.

_[See also the `std::slice` module](slice/index.html "mod std::slice")._

Slices are a view into a block of memory represented as a pointer and a length.

```
// slicing a Vec
let vec = vec![1, 2, 3];
let int_slice = &vec[..];
// coercing an array to a slice
let str_slice: &[&str] = &["one", "two", "three"];
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0A//+slicing+a+Vec%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++let+vec+=+vec!%5B1,+2,+3%5D;%0A++++let+int_slice+=+%26vec%5B..%5D;%0A++++//+coercing+an+array+to+a+slice%0A++++let+str_slice:+%26%5B%26str%5D+=+%26%5B%22one%22,+%22two%22,+%22three%22%5D;%0A%7D&edition=2021)

Slices are either mutable or shared. The shared slice type is `&[T]`, while the mutable slice type is `&mut [T]`, where `T` represents the element type. For example, you can mutate the block of memory that a mutable slice points to:

```
let mut x = [1, 2, 3];
let x = &mut x[..]; // Take a full slice of `x`.
x[1] = 7;
assert_eq!(x, &[1, 7, 3]);
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++let+mut+x+=+%5B1,+2,+3%5D;%0A++++let+x+=+%26mut+x%5B..%5D;+//+Take+a+full+slice+of+%60x%60.%0A++++x%5B1%5D+=+7;%0A++++assert_eq!(x,+%26%5B1,+7,+3%5D);%0A%7D&edition=2021)

As slices store the length of the sequence they refer to, they have twice the size of pointers to [`Sized`](marker/trait.Sized.html) types. Also see the reference on [dynamically sized types](../reference/dynamically-sized-types.html).

```
let pointer_size = std::mem::size_of::<&u8>();
assert_eq!(2 * pointer_size, std::mem::size_of::<&[u8]>());
assert_eq!(2 * pointer_size, std::mem::size_of::<*const [u8]>());
assert_eq!(2 * pointer_size, std::mem::size_of::<Box<[u8]>>());
assert_eq!(2 * pointer_size, std::mem::size_of::<Rc<[u8]>>());
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++use+std::rc::Rc;%0A++++let+pointer_size+=+std::mem::size_of::%3C%26u8%3E();%0A++++assert_eq!(2+*+pointer_size,+std::mem::size_of::%3C%26%5Bu8%5D%3E());%0A++++assert_eq!(2+*+pointer_size,+std::mem::size_of::%3C*const+%5Bu8%5D%3E());%0A++++assert_eq!(2+*+pointer_size,+std::mem::size_of::%3CBox%3C%5Bu8%5D%3E%3E());%0A++++assert_eq!(2+*+pointer_size,+std::mem::size_of::%3CRc%3C%5Bu8%5D%3E%3E());%0A%7D&edition=2021)

### [§](#trait-implementations-1)Trait Implementations

Some traits are implemented for slices if the element type implements that trait. This includes [`Eq`](cmp/trait.Eq.html "trait std::cmp::Eq"), [`Hash`](hash/trait.Hash.html "trait std::hash::Hash") and [`Ord`](cmp/trait.Ord.html "trait std::cmp::Ord").

### [§](#iteration)Iteration

The slices implement `IntoIterator`. The iterator yields references to the slice elements.

```
let numbers: &[i32] = &[0, 1, 2];
for n in numbers {
    println!("{n} is a number!");
}
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++let+numbers:+%26%5Bi32%5D+=+%26%5B0,+1,+2%5D;%0A++++for+n+in+numbers+%7B%0A++++++++println!(%22%7Bn%7D+is+a+number!%22);%0A++++%7D%0A%7D&edition=2021)

The mutable slice yields mutable references to the elements:

```
let mut scores: &mut [i32] = &mut [7, 8, 9];
for score in scores {
    *score += 1;
}
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++let+mut+scores:+%26mut+%5Bi32%5D+=+%26mut+%5B7,+8,+9%5D;%0A++++for+score+in+scores+%7B%0A++++++++*score+%2B=+1;%0A++++%7D%0A%7D&edition=2021)

This iterator yields mutable references to the slice’s elements, so while the element type of the slice is `i32`, the element type of the iterator is `&mut i32`.

-   [`.iter`](about:blank/primitive.slice.html#method.iter "method slice::iter") and [`.iter_mut`](about:blank/primitive.slice.html#method.iter_mut "method slice::iter_mut") are the explicit methods to return the default iterators.
-   Further methods that return iterators are [`.split`](about:blank/primitive.slice.html#method.split "method slice::split"), [`.splitn`](about:blank/primitive.slice.html#method.splitn "method slice::splitn"), [`.chunks`](about:blank/primitive.slice.html#method.chunks "method slice::chunks"), [`.windows`](about:blank/primitive.slice.html#method.windows "method slice::windows") and more.

