1.77.0 · [source](https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.80.0/src/core/slice/mod.rs.html#1802-1804)

Returns an iterator over the slice producing non-overlapping runs of elements using the predicate to separate them.

The predicate is called for every pair of consecutive elements, meaning that it is called on `slice[0]` and `slice[1]`, followed by `slice[1]` and `slice[2]`, and so on.

##### [§](#examples-58)Examples

```
let slice = &[1, 1, 1, 3, 3, 2, 2, 2];

let mut iter = slice.chunk_by(|a, b| a == b);

assert_eq!(iter.next(), Some(&[1, 1, 1][..]));
assert_eq!(iter.next(), Some(&[3, 3][..]));
assert_eq!(iter.next(), Some(&[2, 2, 2][..]));
assert_eq!(iter.next(), None);
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++let+slice+=+%26%5B1,+1,+1,+3,+3,+2,+2,+2%5D;%0A++++%0A++++let+mut+iter+=+slice.chunk_by(%7Ca,+b%7C+a+==+b);%0A++++%0A++++assert_eq!(iter.next(),+Some(%26%5B1,+1,+1%5D%5B..%5D));%0A++++assert_eq!(iter.next(),+Some(%26%5B3,+3%5D%5B..%5D));%0A++++assert_eq!(iter.next(),+Some(%26%5B2,+2,+2%5D%5B..%5D));%0A++++assert_eq!(iter.next(),+None);%0A%7D&edition=2021)

This method can be used to extract the sorted subslices:

```
let slice = &[1, 1, 2, 3, 2, 3, 2, 3, 4];

let mut iter = slice.chunk_by(|a, b| a <= b);

assert_eq!(iter.next(), Some(&[1, 1, 2, 3][..]));
assert_eq!(iter.next(), Some(&[2, 3][..]));
assert_eq!(iter.next(), Some(&[2, 3, 4][..]));
assert_eq!(iter.next(), None);
```

