1.27.0 · [source](https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.80.0/src/core/slice/mod.rs.html#2298-2300)

Returns an iterator over subslices separated by elements that match `pred`, starting at the end of the slice and working backwards. The matched element is not contained in the subslices.

##### [§](#examples-70)Examples

```
let slice = [11, 22, 33, 0, 44, 55];
let mut iter = slice.rsplit(|num| *num == 0);

assert_eq!(iter.next().unwrap(), &[44, 55]);
assert_eq!(iter.next().unwrap(), &[11, 22, 33]);
assert_eq!(iter.next(), None);
```

[Run](https://play.rust-lang.org/?code=%23!%5Ballow(unused)%5D%0Afn+main()+%7B%0A++++let+slice+=+%5B11,+22,+33,+0,+44,+55%5D;%0A++++let+mut+iter+=+slice.rsplit(%7Cnum%7C+*num+==+0);%0A++++%0A++++assert_eq!(iter.next().unwrap(),+%26%5B44,+55%5D);%0A++++assert_eq!(iter.next().unwrap(),+%26%5B11,+22,+33%5D);%0A++++assert_eq!(iter.next(),+None);%0A%7D&edition=2021)

As with `split()`, if the first or last element is matched, an empty slice will be the first (or last) item returned by the iterator.

```
let v = &[0, 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8];
let mut it = v.rsplit(|n| *n % 2 == 0);
assert_eq!(it.next().unwrap(), &[]);
assert_eq!(it.next().unwrap(), &[3, 5]);
assert_eq!(it.next().unwrap(), &[1, 1]);
assert_eq!(it.next().unwrap(), &[]);
assert_eq!(it.next(), None);
```

